	.story This was the second week of my paternity leave and that gave me plenty of free time with Audrey. I watched her sleep more than half the time. She has many fine hairs covering her skin which are mesmerising to watch. When she is awake, we read to her "The Cat in the Hat" and "The Cat in the Hat Comes Back". They are funny stories. She may not understand them now but someday she will. Apart from reading, we sing songs to her too. My favourites are "Spring is Here", "In the City" and "Little Virus". I think she likes them too as she listen with a serious face. She likes her toes to be counted. When I pull on it one by one, she is figuring out what is happening. Her toes are so tiny, it is incredible to watch them.

	.photoset(data-layout="W")
		img(src="https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-YZpwTm1JxhA/WJwNXNiqGiI/AAAAAAABdUw/bJc7zxp6HkQFsPEvaQYpirsHmIoEofDFQCLcB/s1600/IMG_8099.jpg")

	.story #[.ellis] The feeling of being a mother has still yet to settle in me. Really? Am I a mother now? Do I really have a daughter? These questions, I probably never thought they would be a 'yes'. It feels unreal. Will I be a good mother? Will I be able to take good care of Audrey? Even more questions for myself now... 

	.story Cooping myself in the house for straight 3 weeks is a feat. Oh my... I feel so emo sometimes that I cannot even get out of house. The only time I am out is when I dispose of rubbish. This is terrible and makes me so grumpy. That is why I am really counting down to the end of confinement. Although I think the daily routine will not change much after confinement, I still look forward to it, at least I can eat things I want to eat and go out groceries shopping. 

